In [ ]:
Train-Test Splitting Data Now before we clean our data like we have done previously, we will need to take an extra step where we split our data into a training set and a testing split. We need to do this in order to effectively evaluate the performance of our machine learning model. The specific reason why is essentially when we train a model on data, it is possible that the model becomes really good at predicting only the data we used to train it, however when we try to make predictions using new data, the model actually doesn't know how to generalize to new data, and it cannot accurately predict this data. This phenomenon is called overfitting, and it is one of the most common problems encountered by models. We can only check for overfitting if we check the performance of the model on data we haven't trained it on, hence the test set. Thankfully, it is relatively easy to split our data using train_test_split from scikit-learn, as can be seen below.
In [2]:
# X is what we are using for prediction, and y is what is being predicted
# We are trying to predict calories, so that'll be our y
X = sb_full_menu.loc[:, sb_full_menu.columns!='Calories'] # All columns except Calories
y = sb_full_menu.loc[:, 'Calories']
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.25, random_state=24) 
# We'll have a test size of 25% of the data
In [ ]:
Will our data split, we are ready to start cleaning it. We won't need to touch either of them, but we'll essentially do the same transformations to both X's. If you're wondering why we don't just apply all the transformations and then split the data, some of the methods we used rely on transforming the data using information from the whole dataset. This means that if we split the data later then our test set would have been affected by our training data, which introduces what's called data leakage. To avoid this, we'll apply the transformations separately.
In [3]:
# Data Cleaning

# Replace troublesome entry
X_train.loc[237, 'Total Fat'] = '3.2'

def data_cleaning(df):
    data = df.copy()
    # Add "0." in front
    data['Vitamin A (% DV)'] = "0." + data['Vitamin A (% DV)']
    data['Vitamin C (% DV)'] = "0." + data['Vitamin C (% DV)']
    data['Calcium (% DV)'] = "0." + data['Calcium (% DV)']
    data['Iron (% DV)'] = "0." + data['Iron (% DV)']
    # Remove "%" from percent columns
    data = data.replace({'Vitamin A (% DV)': {'%': ''}, 'Vitamin C (% DV)': {'%': ''},
                                     'Calcium (% DV)': {'%': ''}, 'Iron (% DV)': {'%': ''}}, regex=True)

    # 'Iron (% DV)' includes percentages in the form of #.00%, so we will need to do some more work
    data = data.replace({'Iron (% DV)': {'.00': ''}}, regex=True)
    # Impute None for "Varies" because we don't know value
    data = data.replace({'Caffeine': {'Varies': None, 'varies': None}})
    # Now we will convert the columns to a number format using the .to_numeric function
    # We use the .apply function to apply .to_numeric to multiple columns
    columns_to_change = ['Total Fat', 'Caffeine', 'Vitamin A (% DV)', 'Vitamin C (% DV)', 'Calcium (% DV)',
                         'Iron (% DV)']
    data[columns_to_change] = data[columns_to_change].apply(pd.to_numeric)

    # Iterative Imputation
    iter_imputer = IterativeImputer(missing_values=np.nan, max_iter=10, verbose=0, imputation_order='roman', 
                                    random_state=24)
    data_num = data.select_dtypes(include=['int16', 'int32', 'int64', 'float16', 'float32', 'float64'])
    imp_num = pd.DataFrame(iter_imputer.fit_transform(data_num), columns=data_num.columns, index=data.index)
    data.iloc[:,3:] = imp_num
    print("Done!")
    return(data)
  
X_train_clean = data_cleaning(X_train)
X_test_clean = data_cleaning(X_test)

Done!

Dealing With Categorical Variables At this point, we will also want to convert our categorical variables to a numerical format, as most machine learning models can only work with numbers. It's important to point out that encoding categorical variables is a step necessary for machine learning, but is detrimental for visualizing the data. The first step is figuring out how many unique values are in each categorical column. The number of unique values in a column is referred to the cardinality of the column. To find this value, we can use the .nunique() and .unique attributes. Note: .nunique() is a function for the entire dataset or multiple columns, while .unique is an attribute of a singular column.
In [4]:

In [ ]:
Doing this, we can see that pretty much all the categorical columns have quite a few different values. This is bad news if we wanted to apply the one-hot encoding you learned about in the workshop because it would mean that we would add a column for every single unique value. If we were to do this for the first dataset then we would have an additional 55 columns, more than triple the original amount! This can introduce problems with some machine learning algorithms, and frankly is just hard to work with in general, so we will only apply one-hot encoding to the lowest cardinality column, Beverage_category

In [ ]:
So what should we do with the other columns? Well we're going to get fairly advanced, and use what's known as a hashing encoder. We won't cover how exactly the hashing encoder works, all you need to know is that it allows us to effectively encode categorical columns without using as many columns as one-hot encoding.
In [7]:
# n_components determines how many columns you'll have afterward, here we'll transform 2 columns into 8 columns
hash_encoder = HashingEncoder(cols=['Beverage', 'Beverage_prep'], n_components=8)
X_train_pro = hash_encoder.fit_transform(X_train_pro)
X_test_pro = hash_encoder.fit_transform(X_test_pro)
X_pro_colnames = X_test_pro.columns.tolist() # We'll use this line later to keep column names

In [ ]:
It's important to know that using a hash encoder isn't necessarily free. Having fewer columns can lead to less information, and it can also cause hash collision, where the same hash value represents multiple data values. However, the benefits of hash encoding outweigh the potential downsides, especially on a smaller dataset like this.

Setting up a Machine Learning Model We have now transformed our data to the point where we are finally ready to fit an actual machine learning model to the data! Now there are 1000s of machine learning models available to us, and it can be hard to decide which one will perform best. In fact, it is common for people to test many models to see which one performs best. For today, we will test out 3 different models, and then evaluate the model. Our first model will be one of the simplest: linear regression. You may recognize this as a line of best fit, and perhaps it doesn't even seem like a machine learning model at all. However, it accomplishes the same basic goal of predicting new values using our data.
In [11]:
# Function to print out evaluation metrics
def eval_model(y_test, predictions):
    print("RMSE: ", np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test, predictions)))
    print("MAE: ", mean_absolute_error(y_test, predictions))
    print("Max Error: ", max_error(y_test, predictions))
    print("Percentage Error:", round(mean_absolute_error(y_test, predictions) / sb_full_menu['Calories'].mean(), 5))
    return None

In [ ]:
Looking down the first column, we can see all the correlations for Calories, and you'll notice that the top most important features in our 3 models, Sugars and Cholesterol, are the most highly correlated with Calories. So why don't we see both Sugars and Cholesterol as at the top for each model? Well, if we look at the correlation between these two variables, you'll see that it's equal to 0.98! What this means is that they are essentially giving the exact same information as each other, so including both is as good as including only one variable. You'll also notice that some of the values in the weight column are almost zero. We can for sure drop any variable for a model in which the interval of the weight includes zero. To drop unimportant variables from our model, we can use scikit-learn's SelectFromModel function which selects the subset of data with the highest weights.
In [18]:

# Calculating residuals
resid_lasso = y_test - lasso_pred
resid_lmean = sum(resid_lasso)/len(resid_lasso)
resid_ridge = y_test - ridge_pred
resid_rmean = sum(resid_ridge)/len(resid_ridge)
resid_elastic = y_test - elastic_net_pred
resid_emean = sum(resid_elastic)/len(resid_elastic)

sns.set_theme(style='whitegrid')
sns.displot(resid_lasso, kde=True).set(title="Mean: " + str(resid_lmean), xlabel="Residual Value")
sns.displot(resid_ridge, kde=True).set(title="Mean: " + str(resid_rmean), xlabel="Residual Value")
sns.displot(resid_elastic, kde=True).set(title="Mean: " + str(resid_emean), xlabel="Residual Value")
plt.show()

threshold_values = [0.0001, 0.0008, 0.0015, 0.002, 0.005, 0.015, 0.05]
maes = []
for value in threshold_values:
    select = SelectFromModel(ridge_perm, threshold=value, prefit=True)
    X_train_select = pd.DataFrame(select.transform(X_train_pro))
    X_test_select = pd.DataFrame(select.transform(X_test_pro))

    # Adding back names to columns
    sel_cols = [X_train_pro.columns[i] for i in range(len(X_train_pro.columns)) if select.get_support()[i]]
    sel_name = {}
    for idx in range(len(sel_cols)):
        sel_name[idx] = sel_cols[idx]
    X_train_select = X_train_select.rename(columns=sel_name)
    X_test_select = X_test_select.rename(columns=sel_name)
    X_train_select.head()

    print("Threshold: ", value)
    ridge = RidgeCV(alphas=(0.1,1.0,10.0),cv=None, scoring='neg_root_mean_squared_error')
    ridge.fit(X_train_select, y_train)
    ridge_pred = ridge.predict(X_test_select)
    eval_model(y_test, ridge_pred)
    maes.append(mean_absolute_error(y_test, ridge_pred))
    print("\n")
print(maes)

In [ ]:
Now looking at the graph, we can clearly see that the minimum error occurs with a threshold of 0.0008, so this is what we would use for the final model using ridge regression. Our original model and the ridge regression model are similar in terms of performance, so it is a tossup of what we would use.ConclusionWe now have a working machine learning model that is able to predict the calories of a food menu item within ~7% of the true value on average. Considering the limited amount of data we are working with, this is quite good performance
